				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Therefore, a level 65 magician can combat any MOB that has a DPS lower than 140.00 as long as he has mana.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">This statement is misleading and I do not see the relevence of it in EQ.
<br />

<br />
Based on that statement, a mage would assume that if he could heal his pet faster than a mob was damaging it, he could combat it, and win.
<br />

<br />
1)I'm not sure about anyone else, but normally when I 'combat' a mob, I intend to kill it, not heal my pet until I am out of mana then run for my life or gate.  This is rarely done by simply sending in your pet and healing it.
<br />

<br />
2)The statement doesn't take into account such in-game features as fizzles, adds, enrage, or simply failing the encounter for any number of reasons, <span style="font-weight: bold">none</span> of which have anything to do with a magician's ability to out-heal his pet vs a mob's dps.
<br />

<br />
3)I don't know any mages that enter an encounter with a solid number on a mob's dps.  I asked around.  We all pretty much agree that we know the area, possibility of adds, escape routes and most importantly, the level and class of the mob before we try to kill it.  Mobs hits can never be (nor should they ever be) relegated to an average since their dps output doesn't follow a bell curve.  This becomes increasingly important as you encounter more difficult mobs.
<br />

<br />
4)When an add breaks mez on a raid and starts wiping the enchanters, then goes after the clerics, do you think about its dps vs your current mana (to heal your pet) or do you tell your pet to attack it to give your clerics time to camp out?<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=195890" target="_blank" class="postlink">Aamen Palantir</a>
